  "signature": "ed25519:b7d3e9a2c5f1084e6b3d9a2c5f1084e6b3d9a2c5f1084e6b3d9a2c5f1084e6b",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must be verified and documented under an SQA plan consistent with MRL 2 requirements; version control and regression testing logs required.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is deployed under a documented SQA plan including version-controlled source, automated regression suite, and release notes. Achieved gradation satisfies MRL 2 threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code must pass at least one published benchmark with documented order-of-accuracy confirmation for the governing equations used in the hemolysis simulation.",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the Navier-Stokes solver and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Second-order spatial accuracy confirmed on structured hexahedral meshes."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for the hemolysis index QoI must be below 5% on the fine grid; at least three systematically refined meshes required.",
      "rationale": "Three meshes (2.1M, 5.8M, 14.3M cells) were evaluated. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI of 2.8% on the fine mesh for the normalized index of hemolysis, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement and achieving gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) must be documented with measurement uncertainty and must bracket the intended CPB operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench test data (Hariharan et al. 2011) provides inlet flow rates of 2–8 L/min and speeds of 2500–3500 RPM with documented measurement uncertainty. Conditions bracket the CPB operating envelope defined in the bound requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index must agree with experimental measurements within combined simulation and experimental uncertainty bands at all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis falls within experimental uncertainty at 8 of 9 operating points. The single outlier at 2500 RPM / 8 L/min is within 1.4x experimental uncertainty and is documented as an acceptable deviation at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The simulated QoIs (normalized index of hemolysis, wall shear stress distributions) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint of red blood cell damage under CPB conditions.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis is the accepted surrogate for RBC damage in CPB device assessment per FDA guidance. Wall shear stress and exposure time distributions are mechanistically linked to the power-law hemolysis model, establishing direct QoI relevance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, comparable blood analog fluid, and operating conditions representative of clinical CPB use.",
      "rationale": "Validation uses the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to the simulation domain. A glycerol-water blood analog (matching viscosity and density) was used in experiments. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB range, confirming validation-to-COU relevance at gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations is sufficient at MRL 2 without formal solver error quantification.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, formal numerical solver error quantification beyond residual monitoring is not required. Steady-state residuals converge below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and scalar transport. Factor scoped to gradation 1 per MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition inputs traceable to source documents.",
      "rationale": "MRL 2 does not require formal use-error analysis beyond peer review of simulation setup. A second qualified analyst reviewed boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings against source documents. Gradation 1 achieved and accepted."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The power-law hemolysis model and RANS turbulence closure must be justified by literature evidence for rotating blood-contacting device applications.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is the accepted standard for CFD hemolysis prediction in rotary blood pumps per published literature and FDA technical reports. k-omega SST turbulence model is validated for swirling confined flows. Model form adequacy is established by prior literature without additional assessment required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Nominal values for fluid properties and boundary conditions must be traceable to published sources or device specifications.",
      "rationale": "Blood analog fluid properties are sourced from Brookshier and Tarbell (1993). Pump geometry is the published FDA benchmark geometry. Inlet velocity profiles derived from flow meter measurements. All inputs traceable; sensitivity analysis not required at MRL 2 gradation 1."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental data must originate from a documented test protocol with identified sample preparation procedures.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data (Hariharan et al. 2011) is sourced from a published, peer-reviewed protocol. Sample preparation (blood analog preparation, pump priming) is documented in the reference. Gradation 1 is sufficient and achieved at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters must match experimental conditions within documented tolerances for the primary QoI operating points.",
      "rationale": "Rotational speed, volumetric flow rate, and fluid temperature are matched to experimental values within instrument tolerances (±10 RPM, ±0.05 L/min, ±0.5°C). Equivalency is confirmed by direct comparison table in the validation report. Formal uncertainty propagation not required at MRL 2 gradation 1."
    }
  ],
